ke class and assertion are removed, the test could pass. While the developer suggests not broadening the patch, I wonder if we could find a way to exclude it without affecting other coverage.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining class loading behavior**\\n\\nI'm considering whether the JVM can still load a class when DirectByteBufferPool uses Class.forName. If test compilation places classes on the classpath, calling Class.forName(\\\"sun.misc.Cleaner\\\") might fail due to package sealing. The error in the stack occurs at the `classOf[sun.misc.Cleaner]` line in the Direct test, not within Gradle. I see that DirectByteBufferPoolTest fails with a NoClassDefFoundError at line 25, which is puzzling. It seems like there's a deeper issue to explore.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_wPKlkkgKqardbFJUw6Ssnh6K|fc_076af53f5326b6eb0169fb26b2cb84819f97ffef94b53cb2c2", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "java -version 2>&1 | head -3 && jshell <<'EOF'\ntry { System.out.println(Class.forName(\"sun.misc.Cleaner\")); } catch (Throwable t) { t.printStackTrace(); }\ntry { System.out.println(Class.forName(\"jdk.internal.ref.Cleaner\")); } catch (Throwable t) { t.printStackTrace(); }\nEOF", "timeout": 20}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"java -version 2>&1 | head -3 && jshell <<'EOF'\\ntry { System.out.println(Class.forName(\\\"sun.misc.Cleaner\\\")); } catch (Throwable t) { t.printStackTrace(); }\\ntry { System.out.println(Class.forName(\\\"jdk.internal.ref.Cleaner\\\")); } catch (Throwable t) { t.printStackTrace(); }\\nEOF\", \"timeout\": 20}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 670, "output": 908, "cacheRead": 30208, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 31786, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778067110924, "responseId": "resp_076af53f5326b6eb0169fb26a75cd8819fae1c60adad03b416"}}
